    <div class="origin-text">

      <p class="reveal origin-opening">Aarthi Sarode arrived here from two directions. Neither alone would have been enough.</p>

      <div class="gold-rule reveal"></div>

      <p class="reveal">Twenty-one years in acute neurorehabilitation -- Shirley Ryan, Stanford, Rush, Kaiser -- taught her to read the nervous system at its most exposed. Stroke. Spinal cord injury. Traumatic brain injury. The slow unraveling of dementia. She learned what the body does when it is fighting to come back, and she learned the ceiling of what clinical expertise alone can reach.</p>

      <p class="reveal">That ceiling was always fear. And fear, she discovered, cannot be reasoned with. It has to be met somewhere beneath the story, beneath the insight, in the place where the body has been holding it all along.</p>

      <p class="reveal">Somatic Experiencing gave her the methodology. Training alongside Peter Levine in Croatia gave her the confirmation. The body returns to itself not because you direct it there -- but because in genuine safety, with the lightest of touches, it remembers. She spent three years training in that understanding. She spent one of them on the floor herself.</p>

      <p class="reveal" style="font-style:italic; color:var(--gold-light); font-family:'Cormorant Garamond', serif; font-size:1.15rem; line-height:1.8;">That is not incidental to what she offers. It is the whole of it.</p>

      <p class="reveal">What she brings now is not separable into parts. The clinical and the contemplative have become one thing -- the contemplative reaching back to childhood, running deeper than any training, the clinical forged at the edge of what the body can endure and survive.</p>

      <p class="reveal" style="font-style:italic; color:var(--gold-light); font-family:'Cormorant Garamond', serif; font-size:1.15rem; line-height:1.8;">Neurozenesis is where all of it lives.</p>

